Prediction Prep



In order to have data shaped the way I wanted it in order to both test a regression, and then apply it, I created 2 different R scripts.

Here is what I did for each:



For Regression Testing


  • No NA values
  • Only values with SWE > 0
  • Snow depth > 0
  • No 5:1 or 10:1 snow ratios
  • No values over 50 inches depth where ratio > 5



For Prediction Application


  • Depth = 0 when SWE = 0
  • Separate NA depth rows from valid depth
  • To NA –> 5:1 or 10:1 snow ratios
  • To NA –> values over 50 inches depth where ratio > 5



Some explanation on what I did

I took only included rows where SWE > 0 because when it is 0, we already know the depth is 0.

I filtered out the ratios where depth = 5,10 because I supposed they are not the real values.

I don’t want any values where the snow ratio > 5 past 50 inches of depth because it is improbable. It’s probably when the depth < 50 because for early/late season snowfalls, when the snowpack is only what 1 storm has left, the snow ratio tends to be a lot higher, but deceases over time when snow from newer storms compact snow from prior storms.

That is shown in the graphic below.





In effort to fit the regression to the values that make the most sense possible, I made the arbitrary decision stated above, and cut out values past 50 depth with a ratio more than 5.



All of my efforts to prepare for applying the regression were to separate the data into 2 sets: for creating the regression (once we proved it works), and to apply it towards who’s snow depth values are NA.
